56
00:04:10,290 --> 00:04:13,730
And because at the end of the
day it's a machine, it opens up

57
00:04:13,730 --> 00:04:15,820
the possibility to scale this.

58
00:04:16,330 --> 00:04:22,669
In a sense, the same AI that's hungry for
context can also produce that context.

59
00:04:23,259 --> 00:04:28,030
If we design the extraction process
well, we can have agents that produce

60
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:30,329
documentation that is actually useful.

61
00:04:31,270 --> 00:04:35,379
Humans are bad at maintaining
documentation, but AI is consistent,

62
00:04:35,380 --> 00:04:37,610
it's tireless, and therefore scalable.

63
00:04:38,110 --> 00:04:40,249
And this is essentially
the architecture hub.

64
00:04:41,029 --> 00:04:45,059
It's a system where AI is used to extract
information from all the necessary

65
00:04:45,060 --> 00:04:49,809
repos to extract useful information in
a useful way and do it consistently.

66
00:04:50,679 --> 00:04:54,779
AI is also used to access that
information and connect the

67
00:04:54,780 --> 00:04:56,919
different bits of the documentation.

68
00:04:57,419 --> 00:05:00,939
At its core, from a technical
point of view, it's a simple Git

69
00:05:00,949 --> 00:05:03,279
repo with a set of markdown files.

70
00:05:04,029 --> 00:05:11,159
Each such file documents some aspect, and
this is done over a set of repositories.

71
00:05:11,449 --> 00:05:13,349
There's nothing very fancy about it.

72
00:05:13,869 --> 00:05:16,959
It's just files stored
in a shared Git repo.

73
00:05:17,629 --> 00:05:21,289
This is actually by choice,
given the constraints and

74
00:05:21,309 --> 00:05:23,649
principles we wanted to follow.

75
00:05:24,339 --> 00:05:28,830
These are the core principles and
constraints that we went about

76
00:05:28,830 --> 00:05:33,659
when building this, so we can
achieve the desired outcome with a

77
00:05:33,670 --> 00:05:36,050
reasonable sort of time to market.

78
00:05:36,550 --> 00:05:40,710
Zero infrastructure means that
there's no servers, there are

79
00:05:40,710 --> 00:05:42,890
no servers to set up, right?

80
00:05:43,150 --> 00:05:44,830
It's just a Git repo that's there.

81
00:05:44,830 --> 00:05:45,780
It's accessible.

82
00:05:45,790 --> 00:05:48,890
There's nothing to
monitor, nothing to set up.

83
00:05:48,900 --> 00:05:51,780
It doesn't cost beyond
the Git repo, of course.

84
00:05:52,280 --> 00:05:57,160
AI native means that there's no
special tooling as well, right?

85
00:05:57,190 --> 00:06:03,080
It's just reading and writing files,
grep, and combined with shell scripts

86
00:06:03,140 --> 00:06:08,530
or Python scripts, we can pretty
much do all we want with these files.

87
00:06:08,980 --> 00:06:11,920
Diffables means that you
see exactly what changed.

88
00:06:11,920 --> 00:06:17,040
You're basically relying on Git log, and
you can see exactly what changed and when.

89
00:06:17,620 --> 00:06:21,590
You have a clear trace of changes of
the evolution of each of the repos

90
00:06:22,150 --> 00:06:23,800
that you're documenting and following.

91
00:06:24,310 --> 00:06:31,460
So you're just relying on Git log And
this also means that humans can review

92
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:36,470
the changes, can follow the change and
this helps in building trust, right?

93
00:06:36,530 --> 00:06:37,740
Because humans view it.

94
00:06:38,170 --> 00:06:42,420
It's important to be able to monitor
these changes, how the documentation

95
00:06:42,420 --> 00:06:45,380
evolves, make sure it's accurate, right?

96
00:06:45,580 --> 00:06:47,050
So we can build trust.

97
00:06:47,840 --> 00:06:52,000
And of course, we want to scale
this, so this is how we scale it.

98
00:06:52,720 --> 00:06:54,010
It's just a Git repo.

99
00:06:54,510 --> 00:06:57,130
Let's review some of the
design decisions that we made.

100
00:06:57,630 --> 00:07:03,880
First of all, we actually started out
considering databases, specifically

101
00:07:03,880 --> 00:07:07,770
graph databases, in order to model
the system because that was natural

102
00:07:07,770 --> 00:07:10,660
at first i-in terms of the intuition.

103
00:07:10,800 --> 00:07:12,330
We actually did some POCs.

104
00:07:12,920 --> 00:07:17,990
We also considered wiki platforms
and other documents embedded

105
00:07:18,180 --> 00:07:20,590
in with the code itself.

106
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:27,170
But it turned out that flat
Markdown files, they won because

107
00:07:27,240 --> 00:07:29,370
AI agents work natively with them.

108
00:07:29,940 --> 00:07:33,780
No need for some extra tooling
for a graph da- graph database.

109
00:07:34,310 --> 00:07:37,810
Git already gives you versioning,
gives you pull requests, so

110
00:07:37,810 --> 00:07:38,810
you're able to review it.

111
00:07:38,810 --> 00:07:41,060
The whole mechanism is there for free.

112
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:47,610
And Markdown is definitely
accessible to LLMs, very much easily

113
00:07:47,610 --> 00:07:49,670
incorporated into context windows.

114
00:07:50,400 --> 00:07:52,790
There's really zero
operational burden here.

115
00:07:53,420 --> 00:07:54,640
It's just a Git repo.

116
00:07:55,400 --> 00:08:00,830
There is a temptation to build a proper,
robust architecture that will handle

117
00:08:00,830 --> 00:08:06,330
load or whatever, but we realized fairly
quickly that we are prematurely optimizing

118
00:08:06,340 --> 00:08:08,510
here, and there's no real need for that.

119
00:08:08,510 --> 00:08:13,730
So we went with the simpler more
accessible and faster method.

120
00:08:14,230 --> 00:08:17,880
The next thing is about
modeling of the data in the hub.

121
00:08:18,380 --> 00:08:22,610
So the unit of ingestion is a single repo.

122
00:08:23,060 --> 00:08:25,470
This is what gets ingested into the hub.

123
00:08:25,970 --> 00:08:30,520
But the documentation itself is
decomposed by different aspects

124
00:08:30,900 --> 00:08:32,550
or facets, as we call them.

125
00:08:33,270 --> 00:08:38,640
Each repo has several facet files,
each focusing on a different

126
00:08:38,690 --> 00:08:41,220
aspect of the code of the service.

127
00:08:41,220 --> 00:08:46,210
So we have domain models, APIs
exposed, events, dependencies,

128
00:08:46,210 --> 00:08:47,510
and so on and so forth.

129
00:08:48,010 --> 00:08:52,330
Now, we c-- y-you can think
of these lenses as different

130
00:08:52,340 --> 00:08:54,330
lenses onto the same service.

131
00:08:54,330 --> 00:08:59,440
They all read-- derive from the
same code and therefore they,

132
00:08:59,450 --> 00:09:01,020
they are connected in some way.

133
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:07,740
Now, this is useful because questions
to the hub tend to focus on specific

134
00:09:07,770 --> 00:09:12,460
aspects across different services,
which is the point of the hub, to

135
00:09:12,470 --> 00:09:14,420
give us this system-level view.

136
00:09:14,820 --> 00:09:20,470
So for example, if you're tracing a bug,
you should probably access the events

137
00:09:20,810 --> 00:09:25,470
and the API documentation for the set
of services that you're looking at.

138
00:09:26,180 --> 00:09:31,260
If you're trying to assess a blast radius
of a change or a new feature, for example,

139
00:09:31,610 --> 00:09:35,650
you should probably load the dependencies
information for the given repo.

140
00:09:36,470 --> 00:09:36,900
Okay?

141
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:43,270
Another consequence of the facet model is
that it allows us to ingest in parallel.

142
00:09:43,280 --> 00:09:48,570
We-- I'll talk about this later, but
it basically allows us to ingest each

143
00:09:48,570 --> 00:09:53,090
of these facets, and if something
went wrong with a specific file,

144
00:09:53,090 --> 00:09:54,670
we can just re-ingest that one.

145
00:09:55,170 --> 00:09:59,210
And to be honest, it's a natural
evolution of how this was built.

146
00:09:59,710 --> 00:10:05,570
We actually started with documenting
just APIs, then events and domain models,

147
00:10:05,990 --> 00:10:11,290
and it's just easier to add another
facet for all the documented repos

148
00:10:11,790 --> 00:10:17,620
than-- rather than modifying a lot of
different files each for a different

149
00:10:17,630 --> 00:10:19,520
repo when you add a new information.

150
00:10:20,020 --> 00:10:26,010
Now, this simple organization of the
repo allows us to enforce a very simple

151
00:10:26,010 --> 00:10:30,890
convention that translates directly
to a deterministic function, right?

152
00:10:31,480 --> 00:10:39,930
Basically mapping a given facet and a
repo to a specific file in a repo name to

153
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:42,150
a specific file in the architecture hub.

154
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:44,830
There's no need to search a database.

155
00:10:45,630 --> 00:10:48,370
There's no lookup that needs to be done.

156
00:10:48,500 --> 00:10:48,990
There's no indirection.

157
00:10:49,490 --> 00:10:53,030
If you know what you're looking for,
you already know the file name and

158
00:10:53,030 --> 00:10:55,280
just go ahead and read it, right?

159
00:10:55,390 --> 00:11:00,690
This is a simple heuristic, and because
it's simple, deterministic, it's really

160
00:11:01,230 --> 00:11:06,590
cross-cutting, and it appears in all the
relevant skills ingesting and querying.

161
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,690
It's also part of implemented in different
scripts in the repo, in the architecture

162
00:11:12,690 --> 00:11:15,320
hub, so it's useful and it's easy.

163
00:11:15,820 --> 00:11:20,170
The ingestion itself, meaning
creating the documentation or updating

164
00:11:20,190 --> 00:11:27,190
it, is actually where we start to
leverage the power of LLMs, right?

165
00:11:27,690 --> 00:11:31,449
So we have an orchestrated agent
which does the ingestion, and

166
00:11:31,449 --> 00:11:37,610
it invokes specific agents when
triggered, of course, and it takes

167
00:11:37,610 --> 00:11:42,109
care of ingesting a given repo by
invoking different sub-agents, right?

168
00:11:42,159 --> 00:11:48,929
Each sub-agent reads the same code of
the targeted repo, but it is guided to

169
00:11:48,930 --> 00:11:51,069
extract slightly different information.

170
00:11:51,569 --> 00:11:57,519
The agent, each su-such sub-agent
writes its own file to the architecture

171
00:11:57,519 --> 00:12:01,879
hub, and the orchestrator basically
focuses on dispatching the work,

172
00:12:01,909 --> 00:12:06,379
providing the relevant context,
reporting and validating the results.

173
00:12:07,339 --> 00:12:12,179
Now, because each agent is independent,
they run concurrently, and this allows

174
00:12:12,239 --> 00:12:14,009
me-- this allows us to run in parallel.

175
00:12:14,009 --> 00:12:18,889
Of course, it's mean, it means
it's faster, and each sub-agent

176
00:12:18,889 --> 00:12:23,589
does not pollute the context for
other sub-agents as well, right?

177
00:12:23,669 --> 00:12:28,669
It also means that if one sub-agent
fails for whatever reason, it does

178
00:12:28,669 --> 00:12:30,319
not interfere with other agents.

179
00:12:30,409 --> 00:12:34,679
The orchestrator can identify
that this sub-agent has failed,

180
00:12:34,979 --> 00:12:40,149
and it can retry that specific
facet instruction, extraction.

181
00:12:40,649 --> 00:12:41,119
Okay?

182
00:12:41,619 --> 00:12:45,569
The sub-agents are very
focused on a specific task of

183
00:12:45,589 --> 00:12:47,739
extracting one specific facet.

184
00:12:48,239 --> 00:12:48,509
Okay?

185
00:12:49,009 --> 00:12:53,349
Now, the first problem we need to
tackle in order to make this useful

186
00:12:53,369 --> 00:12:56,979
and of course scalable, is verifying
that documentation is correct.

187
00:12:57,479 --> 00:13:02,809
Now, rechecking every claim in the
documentation automatically is hard.

188
00:13:02,819 --> 00:13:05,429
It's really a lot of things to do.

189
00:13:06,059 --> 00:13:09,359
I'll get to how we tackle that later.

190
00:13:10,069 --> 00:13:13,589
But we first focused on
more technical verification.

191
00:13:14,089 --> 00:13:19,019
For example, verifying that we indeed
have the documents in the right place,

192
00:13:19,309 --> 00:13:22,979
that links are not broken, that metadata
that needs to be there as a front

193
00:13:23,059 --> 00:13:27,559
matter in the file is actually present
and it's correct, that it aligns with

194
00:13:27,559 --> 00:13:29,509
where the file is located, et cetera.

195
00:13:30,009 --> 00:13:35,739
Now, at first, we built this into the
ingestion skill, basically instructing

196
00:13:35,739 --> 00:13:38,959
the agent, the LLM, to verify itself.

197
00:13:39,849 --> 00:13:44,259
This resulted in a sort of a
linting process that was unreliable.

198
00:13:44,759 --> 00:13:49,829
But since each, in this case, every check
in this case is mechanical, basically,

199
00:13:50,229 --> 00:13:54,039
we changed this linting process to
be implemented in code, in a script.

200
00:13:54,539 --> 00:13:58,679
So now it's deterministic, it's definitely
more reliable, and it's cheaper.

201
00:13:59,179 --> 00:14:04,299
It can run on every update, making
sure we're not missing or degrading

202
00:14:04,309 --> 00:14:06,579
the state of the hub, right?

203
00:14:07,199 --> 00:14:08,519
And this is an old lesson.

204
00:14:08,529 --> 00:14:13,229
Don't use AI where you don't need
to use AI, and it works fine.

205
00:14:13,729 --> 00:14:19,509
Now, an important part of making the hub
consistent, and like I said, scalable,

206
00:14:19,539 --> 00:14:25,329
is to make sure it's always up to date
with code changes The CI process is a

207
00:14:25,329 --> 00:14:29,089
natural fit for triggering these updates.

208
00:14:29,629 --> 00:14:36,189
Since we already have a GitHub action
workflow running on commits and merges,

209
00:14:36,699 --> 00:14:42,949
it was pretty easy to trigger the hub
update process on every merge to master

210
00:14:43,229 --> 00:14:49,289
or main for the relevant repos The process
updates the documentation and runs the

211
00:14:49,289 --> 00:14:55,099
lint Now, it's important to know that we
deliberately create a PR, a pull request,

212
00:14:55,229 --> 00:14:59,429
that can be reviewed by humans, especially
at the beginning when we started.

213
00:14:59,779 --> 00:15:03,449
Establishing people's trust in
documentation is important, and this

214
00:15:03,449 --> 00:15:06,419
is where human review matters, right?

215
00:15:06,419 --> 00:15:12,119
We actually spotted some issues and
fixed them as part of these reviews.

216
00:15:12,339 --> 00:15:19,089
For example, we had a non-standard
pattern for sending events over Kafka

217
00:15:19,339 --> 00:15:22,549
between services in some repos, right?

218
00:15:22,869 --> 00:15:26,239
And this resulted in those
events not being documented.

219
00:15:26,249 --> 00:15:27,049
They were missed.

220
00:15:27,739 --> 00:15:31,649
So of course, after we identified
that, we fixed, we updated the

221
00:15:31,649 --> 00:15:37,169
skill to recognize this non-standard
pattern, and voila, it works.

222
00:15:37,669 --> 00:15:42,919
Of course, once we gain more confidence
and we see over time that this updates

223
00:15:42,979 --> 00:15:49,449
is done and it's reliable, we can
automatically merge these changes.

224
00:15:49,799 --> 00:15:52,379
So not necessarily strictly…

225
00:15:53,119 --> 00:15:58,379
We don't necessarily need a PR
review by humans on every update.

226
00:15:58,879 --> 00:16:04,489
Now, querying the hub is where we
actually start to get the value,

227
00:16:04,859 --> 00:16:06,039
and this is where it's delivered.

228
00:16:06,079 --> 00:16:11,239
Because we already have the documentation
in the hub, and i-in fact, it's

229
00:16:11,239 --> 00:16:17,219
actually useful to have it there, and
people have started to look at it,

230
00:16:17,719 --> 00:16:19,479
browsing the different documentation.

231
00:16:19,499 --> 00:16:22,089
That in itself is already useful.

232
00:16:22,589 --> 00:16:28,389
But we now have the option to provide
more elaborate and more focused answer

233
00:16:28,449 --> 00:16:30,739
based on these documents, right?

234
00:16:31,319 --> 00:16:36,449
The documents, to a large extent,
are a fundamental substrate, right?

235
00:16:36,839 --> 00:16:40,429
The answers to queries is where
we actually get the value.

236
00:16:40,469 --> 00:16:43,809
That's the, sort of the actual
product that we're giving.

237
00:16:44,519 --> 00:16:46,399
So we have a query skill.

238
00:16:47,209 --> 00:16:51,969
It has some variants That instructs
the LLM how to navigate the

239
00:16:51,969 --> 00:16:56,619
architecture hub, how to connect the
information between different files,

240
00:16:56,929 --> 00:16:58,549
and of course, how to report it.

241
00:16:59,049 --> 00:17:03,829
These skills can now be used in
different scenarios and in systems that

242
00:17:03,829 --> 00:17:06,149
are built on top of the hub, right?

243
00:17:06,159 --> 00:17:11,539
Humans can of course use these skills
in IDE or any kind of AI-based tool

244
00:17:12,479 --> 00:17:16,689
to get answers to whatever questions,
and this happens quite a bit.

245
00:17:17,289 --> 00:17:20,899
But also other AI agents can
leverage the same skills.

246
00:17:20,919 --> 00:17:26,199
For example, we have a separate
