00:18:18,669 --> 00:18:21,719
read it remotely based on GitHub APIs.

260
00:18:22,219 --> 00:18:27,499
So I touched this, upon this also
previously, and one challenge we had,

261
00:18:27,719 --> 00:18:32,479
again, was that there was some variance
between the, in the documentation

262
00:18:32,489 --> 00:18:35,059
itself between updates, right?

263
00:18:35,559 --> 00:18:40,149
Of course, LLMs are probabilistic,
they are stochastic in their nature,

264
00:18:40,799 --> 00:18:45,149
and so we… and therefore, they
provide different results on every

265
00:18:45,159 --> 00:18:47,449
run, slightly different results.

266
00:18:48,279 --> 00:18:54,459
So we had to implement some measures
to reduce the hallucination or major

267
00:18:54,519 --> 00:18:56,509
changes that happen between files.

268
00:18:57,469 --> 00:19:02,589
Changes still happen, but they're
more correct and more consistent now.

269
00:19:03,089 --> 00:19:08,699
So one thing we did was to build, to
have the ingestion tool use templates,

270
00:19:08,719 --> 00:19:14,259
structured templates, so the structure
of the documents is enforced and enforced

271
00:19:14,279 --> 00:19:17,729
better, of course, and more consistent and
aligned between the different documents.

272
00:19:18,229 --> 00:19:20,569
We also gave it instructions.

273
00:19:20,569 --> 00:19:24,209
We insisted on every claim in
the documentation to include a

274
00:19:24,209 --> 00:19:28,709
precise reference to the code,
a file name and line numbers.

275
00:19:29,209 --> 00:19:33,299
And actually, this is probably the
mechanism that gave us the best results in

276
00:19:33,299 --> 00:19:36,069
term of reliability of the documentation.

277
00:19:36,779 --> 00:19:41,279
Now, a consequence of that is that once
this is available, this is also-- this

278
00:19:41,289 --> 00:19:45,859
also allows humans, when reading the
documentation or given some answers,

279
00:19:46,279 --> 00:19:52,089
to act-quickly find a place in the code
where this documented fact is relevant.

280
00:19:52,099 --> 00:19:56,309
For example, where an event is
published or event is consumed,

281
00:19:56,419 --> 00:19:58,389
or an API is called, et cetera.

282
00:19:58,889 --> 00:20:04,849
It also provides a higher-level querying
agent the ability to identify the actual

283
00:20:04,849 --> 00:20:10,679
code reference and to go and read the
actual code if necessary, or if required

284
00:20:10,689 --> 00:20:15,469
to do some deeper dive into what's
going on or to a design, et cetera.

285
00:20:15,969 --> 00:20:19,259
Of course, other mechanisms
play a part here as well.

286
00:20:19,259 --> 00:20:22,289
I mentioned reviewing, I
mentioned linting as well.

287
00:20:22,789 --> 00:20:26,859
And where possible, we'd like
to leverage as much as possible

288
00:20:26,889 --> 00:20:28,489
deterministic code parsing.

289
00:20:28,509 --> 00:20:33,549
For example understanding where
calls are made one factor that's

290
00:20:33,599 --> 00:20:38,549
important to consider is the
uniformity of the code, right?

291
00:20:38,809 --> 00:20:44,559
Repos that use internal libraries
consistently and patterns, or that

292
00:20:44,559 --> 00:20:48,669
use established very structured
frameworks like NestJS in our case,

293
00:20:48,669 --> 00:20:53,719
they will almost always have better
results in terms of consistency and

294
00:20:53,719 --> 00:20:55,969
correctness of the documentation.

295
00:20:55,969 --> 00:21:00,969
It's easier for the LLMs to
understand what's going on there et

296
00:21:00,969 --> 00:21:02,689
cetera, and understand the pattern.

297
00:21:03,189 --> 00:21:07,659
Older repos that are less
consistent or use less structured

298
00:21:07,659 --> 00:21:11,809
framework, they usually give
the LLMs sort of a harder time.

299
00:21:12,719 --> 00:21:14,709
So this is another factor to consider.

300
00:21:15,209 --> 00:21:20,739
Another challenge, of course,
is with the cost, right?

301
00:21:20,739 --> 00:21:21,999
Scaling, basically.

302
00:21:22,749 --> 00:21:24,799
Sometimes API usage as well.

303
00:21:25,729 --> 00:21:30,149
Now we know that each ingestion
consumes LLM tokens, right?

304
00:21:30,159 --> 00:21:34,779
Full ingestions of o-over a hundred
repos becomes pretty expensive.

305
00:21:35,569 --> 00:21:40,679
So we created the updated skills, and
the d-- what it does is basically diff

306
00:21:41,389 --> 00:21:45,279
the documentation and of course, looks
at the difference of the code against,

307
00:21:45,339 --> 00:21:50,029
and it diffs the c-- against the current
state of the architecture hub, and

308
00:21:50,029 --> 00:21:52,259
it rewrites only the changes, right?

309
00:21:53,069 --> 00:21:58,259
Other measures we put in to control
cost and allow better scaling is

310
00:21:58,279 --> 00:22:02,789
to selectively, of course, trigger
the hub updates, so not on every

311
00:22:02,789 --> 00:22:07,889
commit, only on merges to master
only to relevant repos as well.

312
00:22:08,389 --> 00:22:13,149
We also have skills that focus
on ingesting a single facet.

313
00:22:13,199 --> 00:22:19,529
So for example, if we change, like
the example I gave earlier about the

314
00:22:19,939 --> 00:22:24,389
new pattern for identifying events,
if we change the specific facet, we

315
00:22:24,389 --> 00:22:29,839
can just ingest that specific facet
over all the repos in the hub, right?

316
00:22:30,619 --> 00:22:35,179
And this is a consequence of the design
decision I mentioned earlier about how

317
00:22:35,179 --> 00:22:42,109
to let's say how to organize the hub
Of course, in case you want to ingest a

318
00:22:42,109 --> 00:22:47,019
large number of repos, for example, you're
onboarding into the hub a set of repos,

319
00:22:47,849 --> 00:22:52,849
then we have a script that organizes
the ingestion process, times it, so we

320
00:22:52,849 --> 00:22:55,559
avoid rate limits of the API, et cetera.

321
00:22:56,059 --> 00:23:01,699
Of course, when it comes to cost,
model selection plays a role as well.

322
00:23:02,669 --> 00:23:06,859
And there's a sort of a balancing
act between choosing the most

323
00:23:06,859 --> 00:23:12,539
expensive model which gives good
results and using a cheaper model

324
00:23:12,549 --> 00:23:19,099
that gives good, still good results
or good enough at a much lower price

325
00:23:19,599 --> 00:23:25,829
Now, so far we have discussed
technical challenges, and these are

326
00:23:25,829 --> 00:23:31,649
all either solved or solvable in a
sense, or on the road to be solved.

327
00:23:32,369 --> 00:23:36,729
But probably the biggest challenge
is getting people to trust and

